---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Compare', url: '/compare' },
  { name: 'BreederHQ vs Good Dog', url: '/compare/breederhq-vs-gooddog' }
];

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is BreederHQ an alternative to Good Dog?',
    answer: 'BreederHQ and Good Dog are different categories of product, and understanding that difference is important before choosing either. Good Dog (gooddog.com) is a consumer-facing dog marketplace where buyers browse breeder-posted listings and complete transactions through the platform. Public reporting indicates Good Dog charges buyers a platform fee of 5% to 10% of the puppy price at checkout, and takes a commission from breeders on completed sales (approximately 10% per third-party reporting). Good Dog does not provide breeder operations software: no health-record system, no pedigree management, no contract templates and e-signature workflow, no breeding-cycle tracking, no offspring rearing protocols, no per-litter financial rollups. BreederHQ is a breeder operations platform (records, pedigrees, health, breeding lifecycle, offspring, contracts, invoicing, buyer portal) with a public marketplace built on top. Different scope. Different revenue model. Many breeders use both today; if you want to end the Good Dog dependency (or reduce it), BreederHQ is designed to be your primary system with its own marketplace surface as an alternative buyer channel.'
  },
  {
    question: 'What does Good Dog cost breeders vs BreederHQ?',
    answer: 'Good Dog does not publicly advertise a subscription fee for breeders. Their revenue on the breeder side is transaction-based: reporting from third-party sources indicates a commission of approximately 10% deducted from breeder proceeds on completed sales through the platform, and a buyer-facing platform fee of 5% to 10% of the puppy price collected at checkout. BreederHQ charges a subscription (see pricing page) with a 14-day free trial and a founder discount (FOUNDER50 for 50% off Pro or Enterprise for 12 months, first 100 founders). BreederHQ takes zero commission on transactions, zero per-lead fees, and zero per-booking cuts. For a breeder placing a $3,500 puppy, Good Dog\'s reported 10% commission is $350 out of the breeder\'s payout on that single transaction. BreederHQ\'s subscription cost per year is typically a fraction of that single-transaction fee.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Does Good Dog do what BreederHQ does?',
    answer: 'No, they are complementary products with a small overlap. Good Dog is a marketplace with buyer-side inquiry management, deposit collection, and messaging. It does not manage breeding cycles, health records, pedigrees, offspring rearing protocols, per-litter financials, or the operational side of a breeding program. BreederHQ covers all of that AND has its own public marketplace. The overlap is "public buyer discovery for available puppies," which both do (Good Dog as the whole product, BreederHQ as one feature of a broader operations platform).'
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I use BreederHQ to replace Good Dog?',
    answer: 'Many breeders use both today. If your goal is to replace Good Dog specifically for buyer discovery, BreederHQ\'s public marketplace at marketplace.breederhq.com is the equivalent buyer-facing surface, plus you own the breeder-buyer relationship end to end (no percentage cut on transactions, direct payment flow through Stripe to your bank account, per-buyer client portal, contracts, waitlist, deposits). Whether that fully replaces Good Dog for you depends on where your buyer traffic currently comes from. Some breeders keep a Good Dog listing during transition, use BreederHQ as their operational and primary marketplace platform, and reduce or drop the Good Dog channel over time as their own storefront gains traction (embed widget helps here). Both approaches are legitimate.'
  },
  {
    question: 'How does the Good Dog Promise / buyer protection compare to BreederHQ?',
    answer: 'Good Dog markets a "Good Dog Promise" that promises buyer protection under certain conditions. Public complaint records (Better Business Bureau, ComplaintsBoard) include buyers alleging the platform did not deliver on protection promises in disputed cases (see the What Buyers Say section below). BreederHQ takes a fundamentally different posture: we do NOT vet, vouch for, or promise anything on behalf of any breeder. We confirm identity through Stripe Identity passthrough, surface credentials from public registries (OFA, AKC, AFA), and accept breeder self-attestation. Buyers see the receipts (health testing, pedigrees, contracts, credentials) directly and evaluate on facts, not on our promise. See /trust for the full policy.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Is Good Dog a marketplace or a broker?',
    answer: 'That framing is disputed. Good Dog markets itself as a curated marketplace for responsible breeders. Public reviews on Better Business Bureau and ComplaintsBoard include buyers using the word "broker" (see cited quotes in the What Buyers Say section below). We are not going to characterize Good Dog with that language ourselves; we cite the direct customer quotes and let readers reach their own conclusion. Structurally, Good Dog operates as an intermediated marketplace that takes a percentage of transaction value on both sides (buyer platform fee at checkout, breeder commission on payout). BreederHQ does not take a percentage of transaction value from either side, which is a real structural difference in the revenue model, not a marketing claim.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I move my Good Dog listings to BreederHQ?',
    answer: 'You can build equivalent listings on BreederHQ Marketplace from your existing program data. If your animals and litters are already tracked in another system, CSV import brings them into BreederHQ; if you are starting from a spreadsheet or from Good Dog data directly, our support team can help scope the migration (support@breederhq.com). BreederHQ listings are powered by your live program records, so once your animals, litters, and health testing are in the system, listings can be auto-generated rather than typed in from scratch.'
  },
  {
    question: 'Is Good Dog a legitimate business?',
    answer: 'Good Dog is a real, funded company (approximately $6.7M raised per public reporting) with a real product and a real user base. Public reviews range from satisfied buyers who successfully purchased puppies to formal complaints filed with the Better Business Bureau and ComplaintsBoard. Both categories of experience exist and both are worth reading before you engage with the platform as either buyer or seller. This page cites publicly-filed complaints as directly-attributed customer quotes so prospective users can evaluate for themselves.'
  },
  {
    question: 'What does BreederHQ offer breeders that Good Dog does not?',
    answer: 'Breeder operations. Health record management. Pedigree management with automatic COI. Breeding-cycle tracking. Structured multi-phase breeding plan lifecycle. Offspring rearing protocol library with 9 shipped system protocols (Early Neurological Stimulation and Early Scent Introduction based on US Military neonatal-development research, Handling Habituation, Volhard Puppy Aptitude Test, Crate Introduction, Rule of 7s Socialization, Sound Desensitization, Gun Conditioning, plus the BreederHQ Gun Dog Development Program which is a Day 3 through Day 364 curriculum with 64 activities) plus custom breeder-authored protocols plus an opt-in community library where breeders share protocols with other subscribers. Contract templates with e-signature and audit trail. Per-litter and per-animal financial attribution with quarterly tax reporting. Per-buyer client portal with records, photos, and messaging. OFA Sync that pulls public results automatically. CHIC Readiness Widget. Scout AI natural-language queries against your program data using 21 specialized tools. Camera-based receipt-to-expense on the mobile app. Rules-based automation across the offspring lifecycle. Website embed widget. Native iOS and Android apps. Nine species in one account. Species-aware printable ID card generator (cage cards, stall cards, kennel cards, pen cards). Zero commission on transactions.'
  }
];

const articleSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "BreederHQ vs Good Dog: The Honest 2026 Comparison",
  "description": "BreederHQ vs Good Dog compared on fee structure, breeder operations, buyer experience, marketplace model, and buyer trust posture. Publicly verifiable facts and directly-cited customer quotes. Verified July 2026.",
  "author": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "BreederHQ",
    "url": "https://breederhq.com"
  },
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "BreederHQ",
    "url": "https://breederhq.com",
    "logo": {
      "@type": "ImageObject",
      "url": "https://breederhq.com/logo.svg"
    }
  },
  "image": "https://breederhq.com/og-image.jpg",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-01",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-01",
  "mainEntityOfPage": {
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "@id": "https://breederhq.com/compare/breederhq-vs-gooddog"
  }
};

// Good Dog is a consumer-facing marketplace / company, not a SaaS tool that
// breeders install. Modeled as Organization + Service (marketplace facilitation)
